The composition, or at least the publication ol a record of proceedings in the senate was instituted by Julius Caesar in his first consulship 11. Augustus is said to have suppressed the publication of this 1011111111. By the time of Tiberius the senator superintending the ‘acta' was appointed by the princeps ¹⁴, which suggests the pos· sibility of garbling the record. Some account of proceedings in the senate, probably much abridged‚ appears still to have been made public in the ‘acta populi 11;’ and the archives of the senate themselves would presumably have been open to a senator. Though Tacitus refers to them at a later date 11, it has been thought that for the earlier period he was for some reason unable to consult them 11. lt is certainly remarkable, that in places where we should most expect a reference to them, other authorities are cited ¹⁸.
